{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608749/1958041301/0888.xml":{"full_text":"CIRCLING THE COUNTRYSIDE\nMiddleburg Torn\nHas New Homes\nBy DOLORES PHILLIPS\nIpselel Writer tor the Star\nMIDDLEBURG, Va\u2014ln\nstead of cutting down in this\nperiod of recession, the Fau\nquier and Loudoun Garden\nClub and the Leesburg Gar\nden Club have added six new\nhomes and gardens, never\nbefore open to the public in\nthe Middleburg area, as their\npart of Virginia\u2019s Historic\nGarden Week.\nRecovery. Mrs. Amory Per\nkins\u2019 home in what might be\ncalled Mlddleburg\u2019s suburbia,\nis the most unique of the new\nsix that will be open next\nSunday from 12:30 to 5:30\np.m. and on Monday from 10\na.m. to 5:30 p.m. Built on\nless land than a city apart\nment building. Recovery is\na small, walled-in estate,\nneeding only a moat around\nit to add to its absolute pri\nvacy amid the modem homes\nthat have sprung up around\nit since it was built by Mrs.\nPerkins in 1950.\nAdaptation of Gatehouse\nArchitecturally. Recovery\nIs an adaptation of the\ngatehouse that stands guard\nat a French chateau but Mrs.\nPerkins has used a world\nwide approach in her fur\nnishing and decor. Imported\nHepplewhite table and chairs\nand Mrs. Perkins\u2019 mother\u2019s\nmarble-top washstand are\nused in daring harmony in\nthe pale blue dining room\nwhich looks out upon Recov\nery's small formal garden.\n\u201cPleached\u201d maple trees,\nforming a high hedge above\nthe wall line, hide even the\nbrick chimneys of the sur\nrounding houses, except for\none small vista that Mrs.\nPerkins keeps trimmed far a\nview of the Blue Ridge.\nHolly trees, brought over\nfrom Mrs. Perkins\u2019 former\nhome. Journey's End, now\nowned by the Donald Mac\nla swarefc Pj*\u201d\n\u2022f fashion\nL.T\nWashington... J\nConvention Motion* and\nsightseeing may take mort\nof vonr time, bat there i* a\nway to select the mort be\ncoming of fashion* without\nsessions of chopping. Callq\nFashion Consultant, Dorothy\nShepherd, and let her know\nthe orrasion and costume\nyou are seeking. She will\nassemble the costume\nand have it ready to tee\nwhen you come in. There it\nno charge for consultation\nwith Mrs. Shepherd. Third\nFloor, Main Store.\nKensies, _ are espaliered\nagainst the wall below the\nmaples. (For the non-horti\nculturist. this means growing*\none side of a tree flat against\na wall or fence.)\nPortraits of every period\nhang throughout Recovery\nand include one of Mrs. Per\nkins as a young girl, painted\nby the Polish artist Gaugen\nglgl, facing one on the oppo\nsite wall in the dining room\nof the first English Amory\nwho came to America in 1600\nas Consul for the Crown in\nthe Carolines and Virginias.\nA charming portrait of Mrs.\nPerkins\u2019 son, Charles, painted\nby Louis Betts, hangs over\ntht fireplace in the lacquer\nred library, where the more\nIntimate life of the house\nhold centers, particularly\nwhen the Perkins grandchll-\na\nJulius Garfinckel&Co*^\nstora Hour, daily: xo .a (alia. 7 Camera apes Iwarrtw until 9:3d p.m.\n\nIn Oriental water color tint* nkr I\u25a0/ 1/\nA fragile brush stroke of color in pink pearl ji WI II A\ni I, i\ndren are visiting Recovery\nfrom California.\nCombining her astute\nknowledge of fine china\u2019with\nher love of needlepoint. Mrs.\nPerkins has used both in her\ndecor. A Wedgewood coffee\naervioe, decorated with the\nflags of the Allies, made\navailable to a few volunteer\nworkers of the American Red\nCross after World War I. is\ndisplayed against the walls\nof the library, where there\nare also two magnificent\nCanton Jars. A Sevres hunt\nbowl, made for Napoleon and\nacquired by Mrs. Perkins\u2019\ngrandmother. Mrs. Emory\nClapp Os New Orleans, is on\na high safe shelf in the draw\ning room. Pieces from a\ncomplete set of Chamber\nlaine Worchester are on the\nmantle in the same room,\nbelow a lovely, oval mirror,\nthe twin of one presented by\nKing George and Queen Mary\nto the London Museum.\nMrs. Perkins\u2019 great love,\nbesides her fox hunting which\nshe gave up last year, is her\nlarge and varied collection of\nsepia Staffordshire, made\nfor the captains' tables of\nNew Bedford whaling vessels,\nwhich she has picked up,\npiece by piece, up and down\nthe Cape Cod coast. This\nset was used as the motif\nfor the decorating of the\ndining room at Journey\u2019s End\nand now fills a whole cup\nboard in the hallway of Re\ncovery.\nWorked in Needlepoint\nA landscape of the Shades,\nthe small house on the Dully\nproperty which Mrs. Perkins\nused on week ends before\nmoving out from Washington,\nhas been worked in needle\npoint, complete with horse\nand hound, and the needle\npoint designs on the drawing\nroom chairs are as Intricate\nas the afternoon bridge games\nenjoyed at Recovery by the\nmatrons of Middleburg and\nUpperville. Probably the\noldest object d'art. certainly\none not used by the ladles at\nbridge, is the English goblet,\nbig enough to hold a quart\nof ale for the lord of any\ncastle, which stands on the\ntable in Recovery\u2019s wide en\ntrance hall.\nIn addition to Mrs. Perkins\u2019\nhome, the other new homes\nand gardens open on the\nMiddleburg area tour are Mr.\nand Mrs. Neill Phillips\u2019 Her\nonwood. Miss Julia Whiting\u2019s\nthe Hill, the William Grastys\u2019\nHolly Hill, Mr. and Mrs.\nFletcher Harpers\u2019 Friendship\nFarm and Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge Teners\u2019 Ardarra\nFarm. The Thomas DeLash\nmutts\u2019 Oakhill, summer home\nof President Monroe, where\nthe house and gardens will be\nopen, Mr. and Mrs. David\nFinleys\u2019 Little Oatlands,\nwhere the guest cottage and\ngarden will be on display,\nand Mrs. William C. Eustis\u2019\ngarden at Oatlands, are the\nother three on this particu\nlar tour, all well-known to\nformer Northern Virginia\ngarden tourers.\nBlock tickets may be had\nfor the six new homes on the\ntour. Oak Hill, Little Oat\nlands and Oatlands will be\nsingle admission. The Mid\ndleburg Garden Club is spon\nsoring lunch at the Middle\nburg Community Center on\nMonday from 11 am. until\n5:30 pm. The Community\nCenter will be headquarters\nfor the tour.\nMrs. Sparkman\nTo Be Honored\nSenator John J. Spark\nman of Alabama will be\nguest speaker at the Politi\ncal Study Club meeting Sat\nurday at 2 p.m. at the Wash\nington Club. He will discuss\n\u201cFar East and Southeast\nAsian Countries and Their\nImportance to Us.\u2019\u2019\nGuest of honor will be Mrs.\nSparkman, wife of the Sen\nator.\nA musical program, fea\nturing baritone Mr. Frank\nlin Roberts, will also be\nheard.\nHostesses for the after\nnoon will Include Mrs. Wright\nPatman, Mrs. Dante Fascell,\nMrs. George Huddleston, jr\u201e\nMrs. Emmet O\u2019Neal, Mrs.\nLawrence Walrath, Mrs.\nFrances D. Threadgill, Mrs.\nTasewell Shepard, Mrs.\nHenry Brooks, Mrs. Charlie\nCampbell McCall and Mrs.\nRichard K. Bridges.\nMrs. Flora Palmer Weber,\nelub president, will preside.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, Washington, D. C.\nSunday, Aran, is, tsse\n\u201c\u2018HeWsIN\nI Spring\u2019* most importont\nheadlines are all at Gabriel\u2019s.\nI Skilled hands shape your\nSm 'Jgs crowning glory to the most I\nMW jMjhSS vHL flattering version of the new- I\nHbupP mfr est casual look. Take that I\nJrjM \"short cut\" to a new you I\nj\nAuk Gabriaf t ferine went! I\nitart et foot $lO ee\nMonday! and Tuesdays\nC~>a\u00a3ue& I\nHAIR STYLISTS SI NCI 19X9 I\n1019 Conn. Avo. N.W. I 5420 Western Asa. 1\nm NAtionol 8-8188 Oliver 6-4620\nOpen Daily 9le 6 I Plenty of Parking\nD-5","height":"29032","width":"18372"}}
